      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Wrong Methods</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jane K Dokko letter on James Lilley's Sept 12 article says methods he proposes for deterring Chinese intelligence efforts would lead to systematic and institutionalized way of mistreating Asian-Americans in weapons labs and elsewhere</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>While I applaud James Lilley's sensitivity toward the Asian-American community, I cannot condone his calls for ''timely investigative use of wiretaps, computer access, independent surveillance and informers'' as a means of deterring Chinese intelligence efforts (Op-Ed, Sept. 12). These practices would inevitably escalate the ethnic profiling of the Wen Ho Lee case into a systematic and institutionalized way of mistreating Asian-Americans in weapons labs and other places.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>While I applaud James Lilley's sensitivity toward the Asian-American community, I cannot condone his calls for ''timely investigative use of wiretaps, computer access, independent surveillance and informers'' as a means of deterring Chinese intelligence efforts (Op-Ed, Sept. 12). These practices would inevitably escalate the ethnic profiling of the Wen Ho Lee case into a systematic and institutionalized way of mistreating Asian-Americans in weapons labs and other places.</p>
        <p>No matter the worthiness of the intentions, the use of such techniques would further estrange Asian-Americans, the opposite of what Mr. Lilley hopes.</p>
        <p>JANE K. DOKKO  Ann Arbor, Mich., Sept. 12, 2000</p>
      </block>
